{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"28bff8ab-e72d-4aaa-8e49-a35425573202","content":"## `UseLegacyV2RuntimeActivationPolicy`\n\nWhen this is set to **1** (enabled), it changes how CLR 4.0+ handles components built against CLR 2.0 (the .NET 2.0/3.0/3.5 runtime):\n\n**Without it (default):** Mixed-mode (native + managed) assemblies and COM components built for CLR 2.0 require the v2.0 runtime to be loaded **side-by-side**. Loading them into a CLR 4.0 process may fail.\n\n**With it enabled:** CLR 4.0+ **takes over** activation of those legacy components itself, using its backward-compatibility mode, instead of requiring CLR 2.0 to load side-by-side.\n\n### Typical configuration\n\n```xml\n<configuration>\n  <startup useLegacyV2RuntimeActivationPolicy=\"true\">\n    <supportedRuntime version=\"v4.0\" />\n  </startup>\n</configuration>\n```\n\n### Key effects on runtime selection\n\n| Scenario | Policy OFF | Policy ON |\n|---|---|---|\n| Mixed-mode C++/CLI DLL built for v2.0 | Loads CLR 2.0 side-by-side | CLR 4.0 handles it |\n| .NET 2.0 COM component | Activates in CLR 2.0 | Activates in CLR 4.0 |\n| Pure managed .NET 2.0 assembly | Already runs on CLR 4.0 | No change |\n\n### When you'd use it\n- Hosting legacy COM add-ins or mixed-mode plugins in a CLR 4.0+ process\n- Avoiding side-by-side CLR loading complications\n\n### Caveat\nIt can mask compatibility issues — CLR 4.0's backward compat is good but not perfect. Test legacy components thoroughly when relying on this.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"77a21af5-8431-4199-a811-41909214053b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a specific CLR (Common Language Runtime) activation concept - `UseLegacyV2RuntimeActivationPolicy`. This is a .NET Framework concept related to how the runtime is selected and activated, particularly for mixed-mode assemblies and COM components.\n\nLet me answer this from my knowledge - this is a well-known .NET Framework configuration concept.\n\n`UseLegacyV2RuntimeActivationPolicy` is a configuration element in the `<startup>` section of an application's config file. When set to `true` (or 1 in the activation log), it affects how the CLR runtime is selected for legacy components.\n\n\nWhen enabled, this policy allows CLR 4.0+ to handle legacy COM and mixed-mode assemblies that were originally built for CLR 2.0, rather than requiring those components to load with their original runtime version side-by-side.","outputTokens":793},"id":"8ee30e96-da16-4b6b-a2d6-4b8be79ad74e","timestamp":"2026-04-04T01:11:23.415Z","parentId":"f0376fca-b197-4ef1-ab60-bc693485e300"}
